
Step 1: Add /dsp/form/engl/tireintf to .update file
    
        + /dsp/cli/xxx/.update


Step 2: Add new tirechip rpcs:
 
   add: +/dsp/form/engl/tireintf/tirechip.rpc

   to the bottom of the /dsp/cli/xxx/psw/client.rpc file.
 
        
Step 3: Add new tirechip exceptions to except.frm

        add:  .include tireintf/except_tire_include
       
        to the bottom of except.frm

Step 4: Find which act_psw.frm the client is using. If it's
        the generic: /dsp/form/engl/act_psw.frm, go to Step 5.
        If it's client specific then add the Following:


.expr pswd_tire()    (
      tireFlag := PSW$ARGV(0),
      exceptExpr := (PSW$ARGV(1),PSW$ARGV(2))[tireMessage := \"%s-%s\"],
      tireFlag = "Info" ? TRN$EXCEPT(200, act_other) :
        tireFlag = "Action" ? TRN$EXCEPT(201, act_other)
      )

and in the .init at the bottom of the form add:

   PSW$REGISTER("rpc.mich-tire-warning", "pswd_tire")

       If there is a client specific one, compare it to the 
       generic, and if possible, remove the client specific 
       one. All clients should be running the generic act_psw.frm.


Step 5: Create initial tirechip database:

        Run /dsp/form/engl/build_tire_config.frm

         
Step 6: Run the tireintf/tire_menu

Step 7: Run the Configuration Screen and select which 
        interface you want to setup:

             Michelin
             Goodyear
             Firestone

Step 8: Setup Datasets and alarms

Step 9: From tire menu run Transaction Screen

Step 10: Setup pswd, client, and an Equipment Gc on your
         desktop. Then run tireintf/psw-mich. This will 
         allow you to send fake rpcs to test transaction
         viewer.

Step 11: Run tire_data_monitor :

         nohup /dsp/sh/tire_data_monitor restart &
 

Step 12: Run Dispatch, generate alarms, and make sure they
         come up correctly on the exception screen.


Step 13: Update Client, and redo the above steps onsite.



